  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Bare life (nuda vita) is Giorgio Agamben\u0026rsquo;s term for human existence stripped to its biological minimum — life that is included in the political order only by being excluded from it. Agamben develops the concept in Homo Sacer: Sovereign Power and Bare Life (1995), drawing on Michel Foucault\u0026rsquo;s biopolitics and Carl Schmitt\u0026rsquo;s theory of sovereignty.\nThe homo sacer is a figure from archaic Roman law: a person who could be killed by anyone without the killing counting as murder, yet could not be sacrificed in religious ritual. The homo sacer exists in a zone of indistinction — neither fully inside political life (where killing is regulated by law) nor fully outside it (where killing has no political meaning). Agamben argues that this figure is not an archaic exception but the hidden foundation of modern sovereignty. The sovereign is the one who decides which lives count as political (citizens with rights) and which are reduced to bare life (the refugee, the detainee, the person on life support).\n",
  "name": "Bare Life",
